She flipped to a blank page and wrote down the date. Below it, she wrote "11/05/648 - 13/12/648."
"Are you rereading memories?" asked Ivory, looking at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you go out for Christmas? It's only a few days away now."
Kari knocked twice on the lantern. No. Ivory had been right. The Ice King never let Kari go out, because she was "a mistake" in his eyes. She had been born mute, and she was the only girl in the family, otherwise entirely made up of boys.
Ivory was one too, in her own way. When she had reported her non-binary identity, it was as if the world had changed as well. She had been given tasks that condemned her to solitude, as punishment for her difference.
Iel had to stay in service to the princess, but it wasn't too bad, because it gave iel a friend.
"It's almost your birthday, I think?", asked Ivory, remembering that the princess's birthday was coming in a few days. Kari nodded, a sad gleam in her pale blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate it?" As iel asked the question, iel remembered what she had answered last time.
No, dodged Kari. Ivory knew it was a difficult subject for her. It was the day she had been confined to her room and her mother had been banished. Ivory was still a baby when it happened, but iel remembered the servants' and inhabitants' outrage. Iel had heard that Queen Eirwen was a good queen, but that she also had this strange ability to predict the future.
"Well... what do you want to do?", iel asked. Kari looked up with enthusiasm. She handed a paper to Ivory. But when iel looked at it...
Painting canvas 15 cm x 15 cm
White, several shades of blue paint
6 brushes of different sizes
Easel
"You want me to find these things for you?" Ivory asked, turning to the silent princess who was frantically typing, shaking her pigtails back and forth. "Yes?" Iel chuckled slightly, seeing the usually reserved princess get passionate about something. It was the first time she had asked for something unrelated to books and that wasn't in her room.
"Okay. See you later?" Ivory proposed, getting up and making their way through the pile of papers and notebooks.
Kari nodded and once again immersed herself in her memories, wrapping herself back up in her thick comforter.
Iel left the room with relief. The princess was finally stepping out of her comfort zone by asking for things that weren't her responsibility, like paint.
Iel retraced their steps through the corridors, trying not to listen to the servants' whispers.
"I heard she's possessed by Queen Eirwen, that's why she always goes into that room."
"I heard she eats children in that room."
"She looks like a man, right?"
Iel covered their ears, because trying to ignore them wasn't working. Iel headed towards the royal painter's room, which was located in the east wing, second door to the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was as intricately decorated as Kari's. It bore a white dragon, one of the six primordial dragons, who according to legend had created Frostfell. It was normal for the painter to display it on his door. He loved the story.
Iel opened the door, expecting to find a normal scene. Paint splatters everywhere, pencils and papers scattered throughout the room, easels covering every last centimeter of wall. Surprisingly, iel saw none of that. The room was clean and there was a red velvet backdrop with a stool just in front of it. On the stool stood Prince Aquilo, who was having his portrait drawn.
"Ah, hello, Ivory! You come to watch your future king pose for a portrait?", Aquilo asked Ivory, giving them a wink.
"Forgive me, little prince," he replied, partially ignoring him, in search of the items his silent friend desired. "I'm here just to collect supplies."
"Ah, is the girl going to leave very soon?", asked Aquilo, "But I wanted to see you!"
"Well, not me." Ivory had found the art supplies on her list and placed them in a box that they had found. "And I'm not a girl."
The prince hadn't thought of that, however. "Oh my dear, you know well it's just a phase! It will pass when you grow up!", he muttered.
"I have to go," they said, suddenly uncomfortable, because of the prince's words, which reminded them of all the bad things people said about their gender identity. I really want to get away from him.
"You're leaving already?" The Prince appeared immediately at the door, ignoring the royal painter's complaints.
"That's not the behavior of a future king!" he scolded him.
"No one will know. The others won't believe you, and the painter won't say anything if he values his life." He turned to the painter for a second, then leaned toward Ivory. "What would you say to a romantic appointment?" He shivered. Indeed, he had received many threats in the past, but never from a prince, much less the heir to the throne.
"Don't you know what the word 'no' means?" he said, moving the prince out of his way.
"No, I don't," replied Aquilo with a smile. Obviously, a prince who gets everything he wants doesn't know what this word means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why want a romantic date with me rather than with others? You must have about a hundred suitors?"
He interrupted her, still smiling: "500, to be exact." He threw his hair back, making it fly through the cold air.
"Then, why me rather than another? I am the palace's threat." Iel wrapped her arms around her body.
"You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen." Aquilo placed his finger under her chin and forced Ivory to look at him.
